Boil a large #pot of water for the @Udon Noodles{300%grams}.

Add the noodles then lower heat to medium-high and cook until warmed through, ~{1-2%mins}.

Once cooked, drain in a #colander and pop back in the #pot.

Drizzle with @oil{to taste} and stir through to stop them sticking together.

> TIP: If you're in a hurry you can boil the water in your kettle.

Meanwhile, halve, peel and thinly slice the @onion{1}(halved, peeled and thinly sliced).

Peel and grate the @garlic{2}(peeled and grated) (or use a #garlic press).

Halve the @chilli{1}(halved lengthways, de-seeded and finely chopped) lengthways, de-seed and finely chop.

Trim the @scallion{1}(trimmed and thinly sliced) and thinly slice.

Trim the @pak choi{1}(trimmed and chopped widthways into small pieces), then chop widthways into small pieces.

Place a large #pan over high heat with a drizzle of @oil{to taste}.

Add the pak choi and stir-fry until just soft, ~{3-4%mins}.

When cooked, transfer to a #plate.

Return the pan to a high heat, adding another drizzle of @oil{to taste} if the pan is dry.

Add the @Irish Pork Mince{250%grams} and fry until browned, ~{6-8%mins}. Break it up with a #wooden spoon{} as it cooks.

> IMPORTANT: Wash your hands and equipment after handling raw meat. Pork is cooked when no longer pink in the middle.

When the pork is cooked, add the onion, garlic, scallion and chilli (use less if you don't like spice).

Cook until the veg is softened, ~{2-3%mins}.

Add the pak choi and noodles to the pan.

Stir through the @Ketjap Manis{2%sachets} and @Soy Sauce{1%sachet} and allow to warm through.

Season to taste with @salt{to taste} and @pepper{to taste}.

Roughly chop the @Coriander{5%grams}(roughly chopped) (stalks and all).

> TIP: If the mixture is a little dry, add a splash of @?water{to taste}.

Share the noodles between #bowls.

Garnish with the chopped coriander.